  ('grove-street-cemetery', 'Grove Street Cemetery', 'New Haven', '227 Grove Street', 'CT', 41.3147, -72.9286, 'cemetery', 'Organized in 1796, Grove Street Cemetery was the first private, nonprofit cemetery in the world and one of the earliest burial grounds with a planned layout. The cemetery is surrounded by Yale University and contains 16 of Yale''s 22 presidents.', 'The ominous archway reads "The Dead Shall Be Raised." In the 19th century, medical students allegedly dug tunnels to the cemetery to steal cadavers for experiments - two tunnels reportedly still exist, one rumored to contain jars full of brains. Secret society rituals are said to occur among the epitaphs at night. Visitors report eerie feelings and unexplained phenomena near the historic graves.', 1796, 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grove_Street_Cemetery'),

  ('new-haven-green', 'New Haven Green', 'New Haven', 'Temple Street', 'CT', 41.3082, -72.9251, 'cemetery', 'A 16-acre park in downtown New Haven that has served as the city''s central gathering place since 1638. Beneath the manicured lawns lie approximately 5,000 bodies from colonial burials, including victims of yellow fever epidemics.', 'The Green ceased being used as a burial ground after yellow fever epidemics in the late 1790s. While tombstones were moved to Grove Street Cemetery, all 5,000 bodies remain buried beneath the park. A crypt beneath Center Church contains 137 people including Yale founder Reverend James Pierpont. Parishioners have heard Theophilus Eaton asking if they''ve been saved, and ghost-like images disappear into the crypt.', 1638, 'https://ghostsofnewhaven.com/new-haven-ghost-walk/'),

  ('evergreen-cemetery-new-haven', 'Evergreen Cemetery', 'New Haven', '769 Ella T Grasso Boulevard', 'CT', 41.2919, -72.9469, 'cemetery', 'One of New Haven''s most historic cemeteries, Evergreen has been a final resting place since the 1800s. The cemetery is most famous for the legend of "Midnight Mary" and her supposedly prophetic gravestone.', 'In 1872, Mary Hart was supposedly buried alive. Her aunt insisted the townspeople dig up the coffin, and when reopened, Mary''s fingernails were bloody and the inside of the coffin had multiple scratch marks. According to legend, "Midnight Mary" now wanders the cemetery at night. Her gravestone bears a warning: anyone who visits after midnight will meet an untimely death.', 1848, 'https://usghostadventures.com/new-haven-ghost-tour/'),

  ('vanderbilt-hall-yale', 'Vanderbilt Hall', 'New Haven', '153 Elm Street', 'CT', 41.3111, -72.9267, 'university', 'Named for William Henry Vanderbilt II, this Collegiate Gothic dormitory is part of Yale University''s historic campus. Its gothic architecture provides a fitting backdrop for the paranormal activity students have reported for decades.', 'Students speak of phantom events like sudden temperature drops and mysterious figures looming just out of sight. A large man has been seen strolling the roof of Vanderbilt Hall - tour guides suspect it is Cornelius Vanderbilt haunting the residence hall, making sure students honor his name in their academic performance. The gothic architecture seems to amplify the eerie atmosphere.', 1894, 'https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2025/10/31/haunting-harkness/'),

  ('skull-and-bones-tomb', 'Skull and Bones Tomb', 'New Haven', '64 High Street', 'CT', 41.3108, -72.9304, 'other', 'The windowless headquarters of Yale''s most famous secret society, Skull and Bones, founded in 1832. The Egyptian-style building is surrounded by mystery and legend, including controversial claims about stolen artifacts.', 'The spirit of Geronimo, the famous Chiricahua Apache leader, is said to float through the tomb''s halls. It is rumored that Prescott Bush - father and grandfather to former presidents - stole Geronimo''s skull and remains in 1918 and sent them to the Skull and Bones tomb. The aggrieved spirit allegedly haunts the building, forever disturbed by this desecration.', 1856, 'https://yaledailynews.com/blog/2011/10/28/what-lies-beneath/'),

  ('fort-nathan-hale', 'Fort Nathan Hale', 'New Haven', '36 Woodward Avenue', 'CT', 41.2827, -72.8936, 'historic_site', 'Also known as Black Rock Fort, this site was a military fortification during both the Revolutionary War and Civil War. The reconstructed fort sits on the original location where colonial defenders fought British invaders.', 'The fort has become a popular haunt for the spirit world. People have claimed to see apparitions of soldiers, hear mysterious voices, and witness green glowing orbs floating around the property. The combination of Revolutionary and Civil War history creates a layered haunting where soldiers from different eras seem to coexist.', 1657, 'https://usghostadventures.com/new-haven-ghost-tour/');

